# I prioritize phone by software over hardware

I've had an interesting shift when I evaluate mobile devices;
instead of comparing phones primarily by hardware I prioritize the software on the phone.

Today, more than ever, hardware upgrades in new phones provide diminishing returns
for ever increasing prices.
There's little practical difference between a new phone and a phone from a few years ago
and savvy people can save a lot of money by simply avoiding the constant stream of new releases.

Software on the other hand is more important than ever and for me it's what makes a phone stand out from the crowd.

## Avoid bloatware

Bloatware is a big problem with Android devices in general.
As manufacturers struggle to differentiate themselves via hardware they try to produce value via software...
But what they end up doing is loading the phone with crap that you can't uninstall by normal methods.

## Better long-term performance

As if that wasn't enough manufacturers also regularly worsen the performance of the device after system updates.
Apple has been accused of this for a long time but the issue is prevalent in the Android ecosystem too.

For example, I've used a Galaxy Tab A7 Lite as a dashboard for my smart home for a while and it worked great.
Then I installed an update and it suddenly became extremely slow, so slow that you barely could interact with the UI without punching the damn device.

::: warn
Punching the device did not in fact help speed it up.
Shocking.
:::

Some manufacturers (such as Samsung) are worse than others.
Alternative Android distributions might be even better.
[LineageOS][] for example is commonly used to revive older devices and reclaim some performance.

::: note
I haven't yet tried to install [LineageOS][] on the dashboard tablet yet.
There's no official support for it either but I've read that there are some unofficial images somewhere I could try.
:::

[LineageOS]: https://www.lineageos.org/
[GrapheneOS]: https://grapheneos.org/


